{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"60b8e3ba-bf46-4e96-b8ed-4284e637092d","content":"**In MAUI, `AddScoped` ≈ `AddSingleton`.**\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a new DI **scope** is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped<DbContext>` gives you a fresh instance per request. MAUI has **no equivalent per-navigation scope** — there's a single root scope for the app's lifetime. Your DbContext is created once and reused everywhere, accumulating tracked entities.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — simplest; new DbContext per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use a DbContext factory** (EF Core's built-in pattern):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   // Then inject IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext> and call CreateDbContext()\n   ```\n\nOption 3 (`AddDbContextFactory`) is the recommended EF Core approach for non-request-scoped apps like MAUI, Blazor Desktop, and WPF.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f6df5b7-35bf-4acb-891a-b70f87f51f3a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common gotcha when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping — specifically why `AddScoped` behaves differently in MAUI than in ASP.NET Core.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a \"scope\" is created per HTTP request. So `AddScoped` gives you a new instance per request, which is typically what you want for a DbContext.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, there is no per-request scope. The DI container creates a single scope for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":591},"id":"b03e5554-f4d3-4b5e-876b-6631ed9ce837","timestamp":"2026-04-09T15:25:10.497Z","parentId":"3f7a6981-bab6-4909-900c-420209267ab6"}
